    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>I had the same problem. Just Install the exact bit of java as of your computer. If your PC is 64 bit then install 64 bit java. If it is 32 bit then vice versa :)</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 4379659,
      "reputation" : 2087,
      "user_id" : 3571619,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/612e22536d5702d1acdcc257e8db8356?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "HassanSh__3571619",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3571619/hassansh-3571619"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1546283079,
    "creation_date" : 1546283079,
    "answer_id" : 53990654,
    "question_id" : 15796855,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Not sure why, but in my case, the reason was because I was running Anaconda terminal instead of the CMD.</p>\n\n<p>After I use CMD and update the path settings as mentioned by all comments above the issue solved on my side.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 13834396,
      "reputation" : 1386,
      "user_id" : 9986347,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4944ddcf5a78a7f29d31fab5001f2796?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "The Real Eng",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/9986347/the-real-eng"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 29,
    "last_activity_date" : 1564851275,
    "creation_date" : 1564851275,
    "answer_id" : 57340379,
    "question_id" : 15796855,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Search environment variables.\n<a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/IiQI3.png\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/IiQI3.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"></a></p>\n\n<p>open the \"edit the system environment variables\".\nthen click on \"environment variables\".\n<a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/nA5Ap.png\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/nA5Ap.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"></a></p>\n\n<p>Under \"User variables\" click on \"Path\" then \"Edit\".\n<a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/DY5IP.png\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/DY5IP.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"></a></p>\n\n<p>Find your Java path and click \"Edit\".\n<a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/KM2hL.png\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/KM2hL.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"></a></p>\n\n<p>then paste the path of your java installation folder.\nMostly you can find it on a path similar to this.\nC:\\Program Files\\Java\\jdk-12.0.2\\bin</p>\n\n<p>Then click OK.\nnow in the start menu, type cmd.\nopen the command prompt.\ntype\njava -version\nIf you did it right,it should show something like this.\n<a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/G4yfe.png\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/G4yfe.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"></a></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 6939011,
      "reputation" : 1140,
      "user_id" : 5326034,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 60,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/be77997b4150802850e69375b916ce86?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Ganesh",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/5326034/ganesh"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1575200674,
    "creation_date" : 1575200674,
    "answer_id" : 59125167,
    "question_id" : 15796855,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>I corrected my path variable but <strong>command prompt</strong> need to <strong>Restart</strong> otherwise, it won't be able to verify the change to the path variable. May be helpful for someone like me. so \n\"<strong>restart command prompt</strong>\"</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 12719877,
      "reputation" : 153,
      "user_id" : 9240694,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/jxpPz.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Prabhash Rathnayake",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/9240694/prabhash-rathnayake"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1583474474,
    "creation_date" : 1583474474,
    "answer_id" : 60558396,
    "question_id" : 15796855,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>If you have set the environment variables (<code>JAVA_HOME</code> and <code>PATH</code>) under user variables, command prompt (run as administrator) will not identify java. For that you need to set environment variables under system variables.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 9261833,
      "reputation" : 1169,
      "user_id" : 6901693,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://graph.facebook.com/672679486236713/picture?type=large",
      "display_name" : "Utmost Creator",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/6901693/utmost-creator"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1613166409,
    "last_edit_date" : 1613166409,
    "creation_date" : 1613061327,
    "answer_id" : 66158813,
    "question_id" : 15796855,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>In case you are using a laptop and do not have the <kbd>Pause\\Break</kbd> button.\nFor windows 10 users with 20h2 and above:</p>\n<p>1 <em><kbd>WIN</kbd> → <strong>type</strong> &quot;About your PC&quot; → scroll at the bottom → Advanced system settings → <kbd>Environment variables</kbd></em> <strong>or</strong> <em><kbd>WIN</kbd>+<kbd>R</kbd> → <code>shell:::{bb06c0e4-d293-4f75-8a90-cb05b6477eee}</code> to open Classic System Properties → on the left side → Advanced system settings → <kbd>Environment variables</kbd></em></p>\n<p>Also for Windows 10 and Windows 7:</p>\n<p>1 <em><kbd>WIN</kbd> → This PC → properties → Advanced system settings → <kbd>Environment variables</kbd></em></p>\n<ol start=\"2\">\n<li>In the System variables section click on New…</li>\n<li>In Variable name write: <code>JAVA_HOME</code></li>\n<li>In Variable value write: <code>C:\\Program Files\\Java\\jdk-15.0.2\\bin</code>, press <kbd>OK</kbd></li>\n</ol>\n<p>I have taken steps 2-4 from <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/users/3139451/vijay-bhatt\">Vijay Bhatt</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/od7h4.png\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/od7h4.png\" alt=\"Adding a new system variable in UI\" /></a></p>\n<p>There is a bit faster way to set a system variable. Run a console (terminal) as an administrator.</p>\n<p>General command synax to add a new variable:</p>\n<pre><code>setx variableName value /M\n</code></pre>\n<p>In our example, we would need to set it as</p>\n<pre><code>setx JAVA_HOME &quot;C:\\Program Files\\Java\\jdk-15.0.2\\bin&quot; /M`\n</code></pre>\n<p>Like this:\n<a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/9alT9.png\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/9alT9.png\" alt=\"Adding a new system variable using admin console\" /></a></p>\n<p><code>/M</code> - flag specifies to set the variable in the system environment.\nAfter command execution, you should see the message:\n<code>SUCCESS: Specified value was saved.</code></p>\n<p>How can I check that it is added?</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Close your active terminal;</li>\n<li>Open your favorite terminal;</li>\n<li>Type <code>java -version</code>.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>You should see something similar to this:\n<a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/UmkG0.png\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/UmkG0.png\" alt=\"Result image\" /></a></p>\n<p><strong>Notice:</strong>\nUser variables can be created w/o having a root (administrator privileges), whereas to create <code>System variable</code>; You need to open a <strong>console as a root</strong>.</p>\n<p>I have used <code>C:\\Program Files\\Java\\jdk-15.0.2\\bin</code> as an example, in your case, it could be different from mine.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 19759665,
      "reputation" : 21,
      "user_id" : 14469141,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/369a9320f10d4a4f12376773cb741eaa?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "NinelSeyer",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/14469141/ninelseyer"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1615949826,
    "creation_date" : 1615949826,
    "answer_id" : 66666360,
    "question_id" : 15796855,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Try this:</p>\n<p>System variables:\nPATH = /bin folder of your jdk install</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/10/install/installation-jdk-and-jre-microsoft-windows-platforms.htm\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">https://docs.oracle.com/javase/10/install/installation-jdk-and-jre-microsoft-windows-platforms.htm</a></p>\n"
  }, {
